The C++ language referenceCompiler explorerThe C++ core guidelinesThe CppCon conference <p>Whenever you need to look up anything about C++ language, this is definitely the best C++ reference. Almost each page contains examples and explanation. Sometimes this is very technical, but with some experience and complementing it with other resources (e.g. Stack Overflow) it is a great source to use.</p> <p>Do you want to play around with different compilers (or different compiler versions) or, maybe, inspect the assembler code? This is possible in your browser with a couple of clicks!  And you can even get a link to share your experiment with whoever you want. Check out the following example!</p> <pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;

int main() {
  std::cout &lt;&lt; "Hello world!\n";
}
</code></pre> <p>Try me live in Compiler Explorer!</p> <p>This is an impressive project undertaken by Bjarne Stroustrup (the inventor of C++) and Herb Sutter. It contains guidance about how to write good code and advice about what should be avoided. Get there from time to time and read around. </p> <p>This is the main conference about C++. It contains sessions about everything. Some months after the conference many talks are uploaded to youtube and they offer a great resource from many perspectives.</p> <ol> <li> <p>You can reach it by clicking on the   <code>Repository</code>  button on the right of the bar at the top. ↩</p> </li> </ol>
